<p>I received data from server in json format, in which contain utf8 string. I use the following code to decode:</p>  <pre>  + (NSString*)decodeUTF8String:(NSString*)utf8String {     if (utf8String == nil) return nil;      const char* str = [utf8String cStringUsingEncoding:NSISOLatin1StringEncoding];     if (str == nil) return nil;      NSString* res = [NSString stringWithCString:str encoding:NSUTF8StringEncoding];      return res; }  </pre>  <p>In return, how can we know that a string is already decoded from UTF8? The thing is if we send a already decoded string to the above function, it will returns incorrect result (sometime it returns nil value).</p>  <p>For example:</p>  <pre> json looks like this : { "name": "Innoviris Demo Session\u00c3\u00a9\u00c3\u00a9\u00c3\u00a9", ...}   //- parse json NSString* utf8String = @"Innoviris Demo SessionÃ©Ã©Ã©";  //- decode NSString* decodedString = [self decodeUTF8String:utf8String]; //- decodeString = @"Innoviris Demo Sessionééé" ---> correctly  //- decode again NSString* decodedString2 = [self decodeUTF8String:decodedString]; //- decodeString2 = nil ---> unexpected result </pre>